Day One Reflection – Basic Device Configuration

On day one, I learnt how to perform basic device configuration and understood the fundamental concepts involved in setting up and managing a network switch. The session introduced both theoretical and practical skills that are essential in networking.

Topics Covered and What I Learnt
1. Switch Boot Sequence

I learnt how a switch starts up when powered on. I understood the different stages involved during the booting process, including:

Power-On Self-Test (POST)
Loading the boot loader
Loading the IOS operating system
Reading the startup configuration file

This helped me understand how a switch becomes operational and how it prepares itself to forward network traffic.

2. The Boot System Command

I learnt how the boot system command is used to specify which IOS image a switch or router should load during startup. I understood its importance in controlling the boot process and managing different IOS versions stored in memory.

3. Switch LED Indicators

I studied the meaning of different LED lights found on a switch. I learnt how LED indicators help in identifying:

Power status
Port activity
Connection status
Errors and faults

This knowledge is important for troubleshooting physical and connectivity problems in a network.

4. Recovering from a System Crash

I learnt the basic procedures used when a switch experiences a system crash or fails to boot properly. This included understanding recovery modes, troubleshooting startup issues, and restoring the IOS or configuration files when necessary.

5. Switch Management Access

I learnt how administrators access and manage a switch remotely and locally. I understood methods such as:

Console access
Telnet
SSH

I also learnt the importance of securing management access to prevent unauthorized users from controlling the network device.

6. Switch SVI Configuration Example

I learnt how to configure a Switch Virtual Interface (SVI) to assign an IP address to a switch for remote management purposes. This practical example showed me how switches can communicate on a network and be managed remotely.

7. Lab – Basic Switch Configuration

Finally, I participated in a practical lab where I applied the concepts learnt during the lesson. In the lab, I configured a basic switch setup, including:

Setting the hostname
Configuring passwords
Assigning IP addresses
Saving configurations

The lab helped me gain hands-on experience and improved my confidence in basic switch configuration and management.
